# Why Marijuana Should Remain Illegal: A Comprehensive Analysis

## Introduction

The debate over marijuana legalization has been ongoing for decades, with arguments on both sides regarding its health, social, economic, and legal implications. While some advocate for legalization citing medical benefits and economic gains, a substantial body of evidence highlights significant concerns about marijuana's impact on mental and physical health, societal productivity, crime rates, and public safety. This report aims to provide a detailed, evidence-based analysis of why marijuana should remain illegal, drawing from a wide range of studies, expert opinions, and statistical data. The report prioritizes recent and reliable sources to present an objective and comprehensive view.

---

## 1. Health Impacts of Marijuana Use

### 1.1 Mental Health Risks

Chronic marijuana use has been consistently linked to adverse mental health outcomes. Research from the National Institute on Drug Abuse (NIDA) indicates associations between marijuana use and increased rates of anxiety, depression, and schizophrenia, especially in vulnerable individuals ([NIDA, 2010](https://www.drugabuse.gov/publications/research-reports/marijuana/what-are-marijuanas-effects-on-brain)). The onset or relapse of schizophrenia triggered by marijuana use is particularly concerning, as it underscores the drug's potential to exacerbate serious psychiatric disorders.

A 2017 review by the National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine further supports these findings, establishing a statistical association between cannabis use and the development of psychotic disorders, with the highest risk among frequent users ([Hsiao, 2019](https://fee.org/articles/7-arguments-for-legalizing-marijuana-that-no-one-should-believe/)).

### 1.2 Physical Health Concerns

Physiologically, marijuana increases heart rate by 20% to 100% shortly after use, effects that can last up to three hours and potentially lead to palpitations and arrhythmias ([NIDA, 2010](https://www.drugabuse.gov/publications/research-reports/marijuana/what-are-marijuanas-effects-on-brain)). Furthermore, marijuana smoke contains toxins and carcinogens stored in fat cells for extended periods, contributing to respiratory issues and increased cancer risk ([Bensinger, as cited in Studymode, 2012](https://www.studymode.com/essays/Why-Marijuana-Should-Be-Illegal-1057841.html)).

### 1.3 Cognitive and Developmental Effects

Marijuana use, particularly among adolescents, impairs memory, attention, and executive function. Studies have shown that marijuana reduces white matter in the brain, which can lead to short-term memory loss and may increase the risk of Alzheimer's disease ([Debate.org, n.d.](https://www.debate.org/opinions/should-marijuana-remain-illegal)). The impact on developing brains is especially alarming, with impaired brain development potentially affecting problem-solving, motivation, and academic achievement.

